To investigate the proneness to PAOs of a new design, the capability to perform the coupled bioaeroservoelastic rotorcraft analysis is needed, which implies the need for an appropriate model of the biomechanical response of the pilot, or BDFT. This model must account for the physiological dynamics of the pilot's neuromuscular system, which depend upon:


the weight and the height of the pilot;

the configuration of the cockpit's haptic interfaces;

the pilot's posture and piloting attitude;

the skills and control strategy adopted by the pilot to accomplish a specific Mission Task Element (MTE, according to Padfield24 a ‘collection of individual manoeuvres [with] a definite start and finish and prescribed temporal and spatial performance requirements’);

a set of elements correlated to the mental activity of the pilot essentially related to the workload level required by the MTE, such as the level of awareness, cognitive state, fatigue, anxiety, and more.
Often, this broad class of dependencies, which is not completely understood yet, is hidden behind the concept of ‘trigger’, or initiation mechanism, which summarizes the stimuli that may initiate the occurrence of a PAO event. The trigger, as discussed by McRuer,4 is the third player in A/RPC, along with the pilot and the vehicle. The dependence of BDFT on MTE is pointed out in Venrooij et al.18

The experiments were conducted at The UOL Flight Science and Technology (FST) Research Group's Bibby flight simulation laboratory. At that time, the primary research tool available to FST was a six-visual channel flight simulator mounted upon a six-axis motion base, shown in Figure 2 and described in Padfield and White.30 Research vehicle flight dynamics models are primarily generated using Advanced Rotorcraft Technologies' (ART) FLIGHTLAB software,33 which interfaces with ART's PILOTSTATION software to provide the motion cueing to the simulator pilot. While the simulator usually requires the development of an air-vehicle model of the desired fidelity, the proposed experimentation required the development or procurement of new capabilities:


to drive the existing motion system without reference to a specific vehicle model;

measure the input demands to the motion system;

measure the angles, rates and accelerations of the simulator pod (i.e. the motion stimulus to the simulator occupant);

measure the resultant pilot's arm motion;

capture and synchronize all the experimental data from the various measurement sources.
